The paper deals with lower bounds for algebraic circuits computing linear transformations, matrix rigidity, and data structure lower bounds, which are all topics that fall under computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The construction of families of matrices that cannot be expressed as a product of sparse matrices is a problem in discrete mathematics and combinatorial geometry, which are also relevant subfields of computer science (cs.DS and cs.CG). The paper also mentions a derandomization problem, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper's focus on matrix factorization and decomposition suggests that it may also be relevant to machine learning and data analysis, which fall under the subfield of machine learning (cs.LG).
